LED Flashing interface with RPI 5
sudo apt-get install python3-rpi.gpio
Place the LED on a breadboard.
    • Connect the longer leg (anode) of the LED to a GPIO pin via a jumper wire (e.g., GPIO3 / physical pin 5).
    • Connect a 220Ω resistor from the shorter leg (cathode) to the ground rail.
    • Use another jumper wire to connect the ground rail or the other end of the resistor to one of the GND pins (e.g., pin 6 or 9).


import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)           # Use physical pin numbers
GPIO.setup(5, GPIO.OUT)            # Set GPIO pin 5 (physical) as output

# Blink LED 5 times
for i in range(5):
    GPIO.output(5, GPIO.HIGH)      # LED ON
    time.sleep(1)                  # Wait 1 second
    GPIO.output(5, GPIO.LOW)       # LED OFF
    time.sleep(1)

GPIO.cleanup()                     # Clean up GPIO settings


Interfacing of two LED’s to Raspberry pi and make it ON/OFF alternatively

Two LEDs: Pin Wiring and Blinking
    • LED1: Connect the positive (anode) leg to physical pin 11 (GPIO17) through a 220Ω resistor; negative (cathode) to GND (e.g., physical pin 6).
    • LED2: Connect the positive (anode) leg to physical pin 12 (GPIO18) through a 220Ω resistor; negative (cathode) to GND.

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time

LED1 = 17  # GPIO17
LED2 = 18  # GPIO18

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)
GPIO.setup(LED1, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(LED2, GPIO.OUT)

try:
    while True:
        GPIO.output(LED1, 1)     # LED1 ON
        GPIO.output(LED2, 0)     # LED2 OFF
        time.sleep(1)
        GPIO.output(LED1, 0)     # LED1 OFF
        GPIO.output(LED2, 1)     # LED2 ON
        time.sleep(1)
except KeyboardInterrupt:
    GPIO.cleanup()

    • Interfacing LED and Buzzer to Raspberry pi

LED and Buzzer: Pin Wiring and Blinking
    • LED: Positive to physical pin 12 (GPIO18) through 220Ω resistor, negative to GND.
    • Buzzer: Positive to physical pin 16 (GPIO23), negative to GND (or another suitable GPIO, e.g., pin 36 for GPIO16).

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)

LED = 12        # Pin 12 = GPIO18
BUZZER = 16     # Pin 16 = GPIO23

GPIO.setup(LED, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(BUZZER, GPIO.OUT)

try:
    for i in range(5):
        GPIO.output(LED, 1)
        GPIO.output(BUZZER, 1)
        time.sleep(1)
        GPIO.output(LED, 0)
        GPIO.output(BUZZER, 0)
        time.sleep(1)
except KeyboardInterrupt:
    GPIO.cleanup()
Use Pin 6, Pin 9, Pin 14, Pin 20, Pin 25, Pin 30, Pin 34, or Pin 39 for GND connections.
